                    <h2>How are we different?
                        IIC’s Roadmap</h2>

                    <p>For applied research to be commercialized, it is essential that the faculty and students have the entrepreneurial orientation. Not all of the academic staff has entrepreneurial disposition. Therefore, to develop a culture of entrepreneurship within the university, IIC is: Holding seminars and workshops to acquaint the faculty and students on entrepreneurship and its benefits for personal and national development. These workshops and seminars are conducted by industry professionals and academic experts (national and international). Providing entrepreneurial skills training to graduates and faculty interested in entrepreneurial activities. These skills training workshops would focus on specialized skills needed for start-ups. These training workshops would help develop positive attitude among faculty and students regarding entrepreneurship. Holding business idea competitions across different departments in the university. These completions would not only inculcate the entrepreneurial spirit but would also bring out creativity among the faculty and students. These competitions would mainly focus on technology oriented ideas and can be either sole departmental in origin or cross departmental. 4. Hold exhibitions of innovations and technologies developed within the university premises for various industries. These exhibitions would help foster industry linkages and help in provision of funding from the relevant industries. 5. Develop collaborative networks with national and international organizations and universities. These networks will help nascent entrepreneurs to access information as well as markets for their innovations.
